@page "/"

@using System.Globalization
@using FireCharts.Models

<PageTitle>FireCharts Showcase</PageTitle>

<section class="home-hero">
    <div class="home-hero__copy">
        <p class="section-kicker">FireCharts example site</p>
        <div class="home-brand-lockup" aria-label="FireCharts brand">
            <img class="home-brand-lockup__mark" src="brand/concepts/firecharts-concept-2b.svg" alt="" />
            <div class="home-brand-lockup__copy">
                <p class="home-brand-lockup__title">FireCharts</p>
                <p class="home-brand-lockup__tagline">Typed Blazor charts with a product-ready visual language.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <h1>Blazor charts that look production-ready without leaving Razor.</h1>
        <p class="hero-lede">
            FireCharts keeps rendering, interaction, and responsive behavior in Blazor so dashboards, reporting
            surfaces, and operations tools can ship polished data views without hand-rolled chart glue.
        </p>

        <div class="home-hero__actions">
            <a class="button-link button-link--primary" href="linechart">Explore trend charts</a>
            <a class="button-link" href="barchart">Compare categories</a>
            <a class="button-link" href="heatmapchart">See operational surfaces</a>
        </div>

        <div class="home-hero__proof" aria-label="Library highlights">
            <article class="home-proof-card">
                <strong>Typed selectors</strong>
                <span>Keep your own models and map them directly to chart inputs without chart-only DTOs.</span>
            </article>
            <article class="home-proof-card">
                <strong>One interaction model</strong>
                <span>Selection, tooltips, focus states, and responsive sizing stay consistent across chart families.</span>
            </article>
            <article class="home-proof-card">
                <strong>Showroom-quality examples</strong>
                <span>The sample app is organized around chart jobs and product use cases instead of generic starter pages.</span>
            </article>
        </div>
    </div>

    <aside class="home-hero__spotlight" aria-labelledby="home-spotlight-title">
        <div class="home-hero__spotlight-header">
            <div>
                <p class="section-kicker">Live hero chart</p>
                <h2 id="home-spotlight-title">Inspection volume across districts</h2>
            </div>
            <p class="home-hero__spotlight-copy">
                The first screen leads with a real chart, not illustration-only marketing copy.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="home-hero__spotlight-tags">
            <span class="home-chip">Multi-series comparison</span>
            <span class="home-chip">Highlight-driven markers</span>
            <span class="home-chip">Tooltip templates</span>
        </div>

        <div class="chart-scroll home-hero__chart-scroll">
            <FireLineChart TItem="HeroTrendPoint"
                           Title="Inspections completed"
                           Description="Weekly inspections completed across four service areas"
                           Width="760"
                           Height="380"
                           Responsive="true"
                           ConstrainTooltipToChartBounds="true"
                           Series="@HeroTrendSeries"
                           XValueSelector="point => LineChartXValue.FromDateTime(point.Date)"
                           YValueSelector="point => point.Value"
                           LabelSelector="point => point.Label"
                           HighlightSelector="point => point.Highlight"
                           ShowLegend="true"
                           PointDisplayMode="@LinePointDisplayMode.HighlightedOnly">
                <TooltipTemplate Context="point">
                    <div class="demo-tooltip-title">@point.SeriesName</div>
                    <div>@point.X.ToDateTime().ToString("MMM d", CultureInfo.InvariantCulture)</div>
                    <div>@point.Y.ToString("F0", CultureInfo.InvariantCulture) completed</div>
                </TooltipTemplate>
            </FireLineChart>
        </div>
    </aside>
</section>

<section class="home-families">
    <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="section-kicker">Chart families</p>
        <h2>Navigate by the job the chart needs to do.</h2>
        <p class="section-lede">
            The example site now groups FireCharts around the questions product teams actually ask: what changed, how
            categories compare, how a total was assembled, and where operational pressure is building.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="home-families__grid">
        <article class="home-family">
            <p class="feature-card__eyebrow">Movement and ranking</p>
            <h3>Track change across time or across categories.</h3>
            <p>Use line, bar, clustered, and stacked charts when the UI needs fast scanning and a stable mental model.</p>
            <div class="home-family__links">
                <a href="linechart">Line</a>
                <a href="barchart">Bar</a>
                <a href="clusteredbarchart">Clustered</a>
                <a href="stackedbarchart">Stacked</a>
            </div>
        </article>

        <article class="home-family">
            <p class="feature-card__eyebrow">Composition and explanation</p>
            <h3>Show what made up a share or moved a total.</h3>
            <p>Pie and waterfall views help the audience understand allocation, contribution, and the why behind a number.</p>
            <div class="home-family__links">
                <a href="piechart">Pie</a>
                <a href="waterfallchart">Waterfall</a>
            </div>
        </article>

        <article class="home-family">
            <p class="feature-card__eyebrow">Analysis surfaces</p>
            <h3>Read relationships, clusters, and operating pressure.</h3>
            <p>Scatter and heatmap demos cover the analysis-heavy views teams usually bolt on later and style inconsistently.</p>
            <div class="home-family__links">
                <a href="scatterchart">Scatter</a>
                <a href="heatmapchart">Heatmap</a>
            </div>
        </article>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="home-showcase">
    <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="section-kicker">Component showcase</p>
        <h2>Each example feels like a real feature surface.</h2>
        <p class="section-lede">
            The cards below keep the components live, but the surrounding copy stays focused on where each chart earns
            its place in a product.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="home-showcase__grid">
        <ChartDemoCard Kicker="Line chart"
                       Title="Trend stories with highlighted moments"
                       Description="Use smooth, precise trend lines for operational volume, throughput, adoption, or any time-based signal."
                       Compact="true">
            <ChildContent>
                <FireLineChart TItem="MiniTrendPoint"
                               Title="Permit intake"
                               Description="Weekly permit intake"
                               Width="420"
                               Height="300"
                               Responsive="true"
                               ConstrainTooltipToChartBounds="true"
                               Items="@MiniTrend"
                               XValueSelector="point => LineChartXValue.FromDateTime(point.Date)"
                               YValueSelector="point => point.Value"
                               LabelSelector="point => point.Label"
                               HighlightSelector="point => point.Highlight"
                               ShowLegend="false"
                               PointDisplayMode="@LinePointDisplayMode.HighlightedOnly" />
            </ChildContent>
            <FooterContent>
                <div class="home-card-footer">
                    <span class="home-chip">Smooth or step interpolation</span>
                    <span class="home-chip">Optional selection state</span>
                </div>
            </FooterContent>
        </ChartDemoCard>

        <ChartDemoCard Kicker="Bar chart"
                       Title="Category comparisons with confident labels"
                       Description="Bar charts work well for ranking, inventory, throughput, and side-by-side comparisons that need quick scanning."
                       Compact="true">
            <ChildContent>
                <FireBarChart TItem="MiniBarPoint"
                              Title="Service requests"
                              Description="Requests by category"
                              Width="420"
                              Height="300"
                              Responsive="true"
                              ConstrainTooltipToChartBounds="true"
                              Items="@MiniBars"
                              ValueSelector="point => point.Value"
                              LabelSelector="point => point.Label"
                              ColorSelector="point => point.Color"
                              HoverColorSelector="point => point.HoverColor"
                              GridLineCount="4"
                              BarSpacing="0.18" />
            </ChildContent>
            <FooterContent>
                <div class="home-card-footer">
                    <span class="home-chip">Vertical or horizontal layout</span>
                    <span class="home-chip">Value labels and tooltips</span>
                </div>
            </FooterContent>
        </ChartDemoCard>

        <ChartDemoCard Kicker="Pie chart"
                       Title="Composition views with calm radial labeling"
                       Description="Show allocation, share, or channel mix using overlay labels or a cleaner legend-first treatment."
                       Compact="true"
                       WrapInScroll="false">
            <ChildContent>
                <FirePieChart TItem="MiniSlice"
                              Title="Request channels"
                              Description="Volume by intake channel"
                              Width="420"
                              Height="320"
                              Responsive="true"
                              ConstrainTooltipToChartBounds="true"
                              Items="@MiniSlices"
                              ValueSelector="point => point.Value"
                              LabelSelector="point => point.Label"
                              ColorSelector="point => point.Color"
                              InnerRadiusRatio="0.34"
                              LabelMode="PieChartLabelMode.Legend"
                              ShowCenterLabel="true"
                              CenterLabelTitle="Channels" />
            </ChildContent>
            <FooterContent>
                <div class="home-card-footer">
                    <span class="home-chip">Pie or donut styling</span>
                    <span class="home-chip">Overlay or legend labels</span>
                </div>
            </FooterContent>
        </ChartDemoCard>

        <ChartDemoCard Kicker="Scatter chart"
                       Title="Relationship analysis without forced trend lines"
                       Description="Scatter charts are ideal for correlation, outliers, and clusters when connecting the points would imply a story the data is not telling."
                       Compact="true">
            <ChildContent>
                <FireScatterChart TItem="MiniScatterPoint"
                                  Title="Incident load vs. response time"
                                  Description="Relationship between incident load and average response time"
                                  Width="420"
                                  Height="320"
                                  Responsive="true"
                                  ConstrainTooltipToChartBounds="true"
                                  Items="@MiniScatter"
                                  XValueSelector="point => LineChartXValue.FromNumber(point.Volume)"
                                  YValueSelector="point => point.ResponseMinutes"
                                  LabelSelector="point => point.Label"
                                  ColorSelector="point => point.Color"
                                  HoverColorSelector="point => point.HoverColor"
                                  ShowLegend="false">
                    <TooltipTemplate Context="point">
                        <div class="demo-tooltip-title">@point.Label</div>
                        <div>@point.X.NumericValue.ToString("F0", CultureInfo.InvariantCulture) incidents</div>
                        <div>@point.Y.ToString("F1", CultureInfo.InvariantCulture) min response</div>
                    </TooltipTemplate>
                </FireScatterChart>
            </ChildContent>
            <FooterContent>
                <div class="home-card-footer">
                    <span class="home-chip">Numeric or date x-axis</span>
                    <span class="home-chip">Single-series or legend-driven multi-series</span>
                </div>
            </FooterContent>
        </ChartDemoCard>

        <ChartDemoCard Kicker="Heatmap"
                       Title="Operating pressure across the week"
                       Description="Heatmaps are ideal when both axes are categorical and the story is in concentration, peaks, and cold spots."
                       Compact="true">
            <ChildContent>
                <FireHeatmapChart TItem="MiniHeatmapPoint"
                                  Title="Call load by day and shift"
                                  Description="Average call load by weekday and shift"
                                  Width="420"
                                  Height="320"
                                  Responsive="true"
                                  ConstrainTooltipToChartBounds="true"
                                  Items="@MiniHeatmap"
                                  RowKeySelector="point => point.DayKey"
                                  RowLabelSelector="point => point.DayLabel"
                                  RowOrderSelector="point => point.DayOrder"
                                  ColumnKeySelector="point => point.ShiftKey"
                                  ColumnLabelSelector="point => point.ShiftLabel"
                                  ColumnOrderSelector="point => point.ShiftOrder"
                                  ValueSelector="point => point.Value"
                                  ShowTooltip="false"
                                  CellGap="8"
                                  LowColor="#fff1d7"
                                  HighColor="#d94f3d" />
            </ChildContent>
            <FooterContent>
                <div class="home-card-footer">
                    <span class="home-chip">Day-hour or shift matrices</span>
                    <span class="home-chip">Continuous intensity legend</span>
                </div>
            </FooterContent>
        </ChartDemoCard>

        <ChartDemoCard Kicker="Waterfall"
                       Title="Show how totals changed"
                       Description="Waterfalls work when the audience needs the why behind a total, not just the ending number."
                       Compact="true">
            <ChildContent>
                <FireWaterfallChart TItem="MiniWaterfallPoint"
                                    Title="Budget walk"
                                    Description="Starting budget to updated total"
                                    Width="420"
                                    Height="320"
                                    Responsive="true"
                                    ConstrainTooltipToChartBounds="true"
                                    Items="@MiniWaterfall"
                                    LabelSelector="point => point.Label"
                                    ValueSelector="point => point.Value"
                                    StepTypeSelector="point => point.StepType"
                                    ValueFormat="N0"
                                    ShowGridLines="false" />
            </ChildContent>
            <FooterContent>
                <div class="home-card-footer">
                    <span class="home-chip">Start, change, subtotal, total</span>
                    <span class="home-chip">Connector-based story flow</span>
                </div>
            </FooterContent>
        </ChartDemoCard>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="home-api" id="developer-story">
    <div class="home-api__content">
        <p class="section-kicker">Developer experience</p>
        <h2>The API stays compact even when the output looks polished.</h2>
        <p class="section-lede">
            FireCharts uses one selector-first mental model across trends, comparisons, composition charts, and
            analysis surfaces. The examples below are meant to reassure both product designers and implementers.
        </p>

        <div class="home-api__list" aria-label="API qualities">
            <div class="home-api__item">
                <strong>Typed data in</strong>
                <span>Map labels, values, colors, and milestones straight from your own records.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="home-api__item">
                <strong>Behavior toggles</strong>
                <span>Legends, selection, grid lines, interpolation, and labels stay opt-in instead of custom work.</span>
            </div>
            <div class="home-api__item">
                <strong>Templates where they matter</strong>
                <span>Use richer tooltip and SVG content only when the chart needs more storytelling surface.</span>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="home-api__support">
            <a class="button-link" href="interactionmodel">Interaction model</a>
            <a class="button-link" href="tablepatterns">Table patterns</a>
        </div>
    </div>

    <article class="docs-card docs-card--code home-code-card">
        <div class="chart-card__header">
            <div>
                <p class="section-kicker">Starter snippet</p>
                <h3>Render a showcase-ready chart</h3>
            </div>
            <p class="chart-card__copy">The same patterns from the examples drop cleanly into product code.</p>
        </div>

        <pre class="code-example"><code>@HomeUsageExample</code></pre>
    </article>
</section>

